{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'cryptic coloration'?","answer":"Coloration that hides an animal from predators by blending with the background","choices":["Bright warning colors","Patterns used in mating displays","Coloration that hides an animal from predators by blending with the background","Color that changes with temperature"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is the difference between a 'habitat' and a 'niche'?","answer":"A habitat is where an organism lives; a niche is its role in that environment","choices":["They mean the same thing","A habitat is tropical; a niche is polar","A habitat is where an organism lives; a niche is its role in that environment","A niche is a smaller habitat"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'counter-shading' in animals?","answer":"Dark coloration on top and light on the bottom to reduce shadow visibility","choices":["Using color to signal danger","Matching the color of rocks","Dark coloration on top and light on the bottom to reduce shadow visibility","Stripes that break up the body outline"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'warning coloration' (aposematism) designed to do?","answer":"Signal to predators that an animal is toxic, venomous, or dangerous","choices":["Attract a mate","Signal to predators that an animal is toxic, venomous, or dangerous","Help the animal regulate temperature","Camouflage in bright environments"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which mammal has the highest body temperature?","answer":"Shrew (up to 40.5°C / 105°F)","choices":["Dog","Rabbit","Shrew (up to 40.5°C / 105°F)","Cat"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is a 'territory' in animal behavior?","answer":"An area defended against intruders, usually for feeding or breeding","choices":["The range an animal travels in its lifetime","An area defended against intruders, usually for feeding or breeding","The migratory path followed each year","The area shared by members of a group"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'operant conditioning' in animal behavior?","answer":"Learning where behaviors are strengthened or weakened by consequences","choices":["Learning by watching others","Learning where behaviors are strengthened or weakened by consequences","Learning by imitation","Learning based on instinct only"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which cephalopod has the largest brain among invertebrates?","answer":"Octopus","choices":["Giant squid","Nautilus","Octopus","Cuttlefish"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'r-selection' in reproductive strategy?","answer":"Producing many small offspring with little parental care","choices":["Producing few, well-cared-for offspring","Producing many small offspring with little parental care","Reproducing only once in a lifetime","Cooperating with relatives to raise young"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'K-selection' in reproductive strategy?","answer":"Producing few, large offspring with extensive parental care","choices":["Producing many offspring to ensure some survive","Producing few, large offspring with extensive parental care","Breeding rapidly in short bursts","Random breeding with no parental care"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'honest signaling' in animal communication?","answer":"Signals that reliably indicate the sender's quality because they are costly to produce","choices":["Signals used only with trusted group members","Signals that reliably indicate the sender's quality because they are costly to produce","Avoiding deceptive displays","Warning calls that always indicate real danger"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'agonistic behavior'?","answer":"Social behaviors related to conflict, threat, and submission between animals","choices":["Cooperative behaviors in a group","Social behaviors related to conflict, threat, and submission between animals","Mating displays and courtship","Territorial marking"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'isothermy' in marine mammals?","answer":"Maintaining a stable body temperature despite cold ocean temperatures","choices":["Using body heat to warm eggs","Maintaining a stable body temperature despite cold ocean temperatures","Shedding insulating fat in summer","Regulating salt and water balance"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which organ helps birds navigate using Earth's magnetic field?","answer":"Magnetite crystals in the beak region","choices":["The inner ear","Magnetite crystals in the beak region","Specialized photoreceptors in the eye","Sensory cells in the wings"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'trophic cascade'?","answer":"How changes in a top predator's population affect all levels of the food web","choices":["A waterfall-based ecosystem","How changes in a top predator's population affect all levels of the food web","The flow of nutrients through soil","How seasons affect food availability"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'appeasement behavior' in animals?","answer":"Submissive gestures that reduce aggression from a dominant animal","choices":["Marking territory with scent","Submissive gestures that reduce aggression from a dominant animal","Behaviors that attract a mate","Playing dead to avoid predators"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'resource partitioning'?","answer":"Species dividing up resources to reduce competition","choices":["An animal defending its food supply","Species dividing up resources to reduce competition","Sharing a nesting site","Migrating to new feeding grounds"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which fish uses electric fields to hunt and navigate?","answer":"Electric eel","choices":["Lamprey","Stingray","Electric eel","Hagfish"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'altruism' in animal behavior?","answer":"An action that helps another individual at a cost to the performer","choices":["Sharing territory peacefully","An action that helps another individual at a cost to the performer","Cooperating to hunt","Teaching offspring to survive"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is a 'diploid' organism?","answer":"An organism with two sets of chromosomes","choices":["An organism that reproduces asexually","An organism with two sets of chromosomes","An organism with a double shell","An organism with two hearts"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'imprinting' in animal behavior?","answer":"A rapid learning process in young animals that fixes a long-lasting behavior","choices":["Learning a route through repeated travel","A rapid learning process in young animals that fixes a long-lasting behavior","The instinct to hide from predators","Memorizing food sources"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'peristalsis'?","answer":"Muscular contractions that move food through the digestive tract","choices":["The process of filtering blood","Muscular contractions that move food through the digestive tract","Contractions that move oxygen into cells","How muscles work in bivalves"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which mammal has the most complex vocal repertoire?","answer":"Sperm whale (longest, loudest vocalizations) / Humans overall","choices":["Chimpanzee","Bottlenose dolphin","Sperm whale (longest, loudest vocalizations) / Humans overall","Humpback whale"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'eusociality'?","answer":"The highest level of animal social organization, with division of reproductive labor","choices":["Animals that always live alone","The highest level of animal social organization, with division of reproductive labor","Animals that cooperate in migration","Animals that share territory"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which sense do snakes primarily use to detect heat?","answer":"Pit organs (heat-sensing pits near their mouth)","choices":["Their tongue","Their skin","Pit organs (heat-sensing pits near their mouth)","Their eyes"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'surplus killing'?","answer":"When a predator kills more prey than it can immediately eat","choices":["Killing to defend territory","When a predator kills more prey than it can immediately eat","Group hunting resulting in excess prey","Humans overhunting wild animals"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'natal homing' in sea turtles?","answer":"Returning to the beach where they were born to lay their own eggs","choices":["Swimming toward warmer water for birth","Returning to the beach where they were born to lay their own eggs","Following parents during first migration","Using star maps to find nesting sites"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'countercurrent exchange' in fish gills?","answer":"Blood and water flow in opposite directions to maximize oxygen absorption","choices":["The fish reversing direction to avoid predators","Blood and water flow in opposite directions to maximize oxygen absorption","Recycling water between gill chambers","Controlling water temperature in the blood"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is the function of the 'cloaca' in birds?","answer":"A shared exit for the reproductive, digestive, and urinary systems","choices":["Producing and storing eggs","A shared exit for the reproductive, digestive, and urinary systems","Controlling feather alignment","Regulating salt balance"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'plumage' in birds?","answer":"The layer of feathers that cover a bird","choices":["The song of a bird during mating","The layer of feathers that cover a bird","The pattern on a bird's eggs","A bird's territorial display"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'biological magnification'?","answer":"Toxins increasing in concentration as they move up the food chain","choices":["How predators grow larger than prey over time","Toxins increasing in concentration as they move up the food chain","The growth of populations in ideal conditions","How cells multiply in an organism"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"Which large mammal has the longest pregnancy?","answer":"African elephant (approximately 22 months)","choices":["Blue whale","Giraffe","African elephant (approximately 22 months)","Rhinoceros"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'echolocation' used for by bats?","answer":"Detecting obstacles and prey by emitting ultrasonic pulses and hearing echoes","choices":["Communicating with other bats","Detecting obstacles and prey by emitting ultrasonic pulses and hearing echoes","Navigation during migration","Finding water sources"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is 'semelparity'?","answer":"Reproducing only once in a lifetime, then dying","choices":["Having two reproductive cycles a year","Reproducing only once in a lifetime, then dying","Choosing only one mate forever","Waiting many years before first reproduction"]},
{"tier":3,"question":"What is a 'zoonotic disease'?","answer":"A disease that can be transmitted between animals and humans","choices":["A disease that affects zoo animals only","A disease that can be transmitted between animals and humans","A parasitic disease spread by insects","A disease caused by eating animals"]},
