{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'punctuated equilibrium' in evolution?","answer":"Long periods of stability interrupted by rapid evolutionary change","choices":["Evolution occurs only during mass extinctions","Long periods of stability interrupted by rapid evolutionary change","All evolution happens at the same slow pace","Evolution accelerates with climate change"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'horizontal gene transfer'?","answer":"The transfer of genes between organisms other than through reproduction","choices":["Genes moving through the bloodstream","The transfer of genes between organisms other than through reproduction","Inheriting traits from both parents equally","Mutations spreading through a population"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'selfish gene' concept by Dawkins?","answer":"Genes, not organisms, are the fundamental unit of selection — genes that promote their own copying spread","choices":["Dominant animals take resources from weaker ones","Genes, not organisms, are the fundamental unit of selection — genes that promote their own copying spread","Evolution always favors individual survival","Animals act selfishly for group benefit"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'allopatric speciation'?","answer":"A species splits into two due to geographic separation","choices":["Two species merging after isolation","A species splits into two due to geographic separation","Speciation caused by disease","Separate species occupying the same area"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'handicap principle' in evolutionary biology?","answer":"Costly displays signal genetic quality because only strong individuals can afford them","choices":["Weak animals survive by displaying weakness","Costly displays signal genetic quality because only strong individuals can afford them","Animals that look unhealthy are preferred","Displays help animals avoid predators"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'Batesian mimicry'?","answer":"A harmless species imitates the warning signals of a harmful species","choices":["Two harmful species resemble each other","A harmless species imitates the warning signals of a harmful species","A species evolves to match its background","Predators mimic prey to get closer"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'Müllerian mimicry'?","answer":"Two or more harmful species resemble each other, reinforcing the warning signal","choices":["A harmless species copies a dangerous one","Two or more harmful species resemble each other, reinforcing the warning signal","Prey species copy their predators","Color patterns shared between unrelated species"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'group selection'?","answer":"The idea that natural selection can favor traits that benefit the group at cost to individuals","choices":["Selection based on family ties only","The idea that natural selection can favor traits that benefit the group at cost to individuals","Choosing the strongest individual to reproduce","Selection acting on entire populations during bottlenecks"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What does 'niche partitioning' prevent?","answer":"Competitive exclusion between similar species","choices":["Overfeeding","Migration between habitats","Competitive exclusion between similar species","Inbreeding in small populations"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'recapitulation theory' (Haeckel)?","answer":"The idea that embryos repeat the evolutionary stages of their ancestors during development","choices":["Offspring repeat the life stages of parents","The idea that embryos repeat the evolutionary stages of their ancestors during development","Evolution reuses old adaptations","Endangered species can re-evolve from related ones"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'genetic drift'?","answer":"Random changes in allele frequencies in small populations","choices":["Genes spreading through water","Random changes in allele frequencies in small populations","Mutations accumulating in isolated populations","Natural selection acting on a single gene"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'allometry'?","answer":"The study of how the size of one body part relates to another as an organism grows","choices":["How animals adapt to altitude","The study of how the size of one body part relates to another as an organism grows","How multiple species compare in size","Measuring metabolic efficiency"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'assortative mating'?","answer":"The tendency for individuals to mate with others of similar phenotype","choices":["Mating based on dominance rank","The tendency for individuals to mate with others of similar phenotype","Choosing mates from outside the family group","Seasonal mating driven by hormones"]},
