{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'osmoregulation'?","answer":"Controlling the concentration of water and salts in body fluids","choices":["Regulating oxygen levels in blood","Controlling the concentration of water and salts in body fluids","Maintaining constant body temperature","Regulating blood sugar levels"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'endosymbiotic theory'?","answer":"Mitochondria and chloroplasts originated as free-living bacteria absorbed by early cells","choices":["Early life evolved from shared ancestral cells","Mitochondria and chloroplasts originated as free-living bacteria absorbed by early cells","Cells acquired DNA from their environment","Complex cells evolved by sharing resources"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'reproductive isolation'?","answer":"Barriers that prevent two populations from interbreeding even if in the same area","choices":["Animals avoiding contact during breeding","Barriers that prevent two populations from interbreeding even if in the same area","Physical separation of two groups","Males competing until only one can breed"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'comparative genomics' in zoology?","answer":"Comparing DNA sequences across species to understand evolution and function","choices":["Cataloguing animal species by their chromosomes","Comparing DNA sequences across species to understand evolution and function","Studying genetic diseases in wild animals","Tracing family trees of endangered species"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'ecological succession'?","answer":"The process by which communities change over time following a disturbance","choices":["How populations recover after hunting","The process by which communities change over time following a disturbance","Species migrating into new habitats","Gradual climate shifts affecting ecosystems"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'genetic bottleneck'?","answer":"A sharp reduction in population size that reduces genetic diversity","choices":["Competition reducing access to mates","A sharp reduction in population size that reduces genetic diversity","Loss of a keystone species","A habitat shrinking in size"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'altitudinal migration'?","answer":"Moving to higher or lower elevations seasonally rather than latitudinally","choices":["Migration driven by altitude sickness","Moving to higher or lower elevations seasonally rather than latitudinally","Flying above cloud cover during migration","Navigation using altitude pressure"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'island biogeography theory'?","answer":"Island species diversity is determined by immigration rate and extinction rate","choices":["Islands have less diversity than mainlands always","Island species diversity is determined by immigration rate and extinction rate","Islands produce unique species through radiation","Small islands have fewer species due to smaller size only"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'competitive exclusion principle'?","answer":"Two species cannot coexist indefinitely on the same limiting resource in the same niche","choices":["Dominant species always displace weaker ones","Two species cannot coexist indefinitely on the same limiting resource in the same niche","Competition always reduces biodiversity","The strongest always survive"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'directional selection'?","answer":"Natural selection favoring one extreme phenotype over the average and the other extreme","choices":["Both extremes favored over the average","Natural selection favoring one extreme phenotype over the average and the other extreme","Stabilizing forces in populations","Random selection of traits"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'stabilizing selection'?","answer":"Natural selection favoring the average phenotype and eliminating extremes","choices":["Maintaining current population size","Natural selection favoring the average phenotype and eliminating extremes","Keeping body temperature stable","A balance between predators and prey"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'disruptive selection'?","answer":"Natural selection favoring two extreme phenotypes over the intermediate","choices":["Natural selection favoring two extreme phenotypes over the intermediate","A sudden shift in natural selection direction","Competition that splits a population","Random genetic variation"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'the bottleneck effect' versus 'founder effect'?","answer":"Bottleneck: population shrinks due to disaster; Founder: small group starts new population","choices":["Both are caused by overhunting","Bottleneck: population shrinks due to disaster; Founder: small group starts new population","Founder effect reduces diversity more","Both result in increased genetic variation"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'reciprocal altruism'?","answer":"Helping another individual with the expectation of future return help","choices":["Helping relatives to spread shared genes","Helping another individual with the expectation of future return help","Cooperative hunting benefiting the whole group","Parents helping offspring"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'natal dispersal'?","answer":"Young animals moving away from their birthplace to establish their own territory","choices":["Parents abandoning offspring","Young animals moving away from their birthplace to establish their own territory","Migration back to breeding grounds","Dispersal of spores from fungi"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'paradox of the plankton'?","answer":"Many plankton species coexist on the same few resources, defying the exclusion principle","choices":["Plankton are more diverse in cold water","Many plankton species coexist on the same few resources, defying the exclusion principle","Plankton cannot be classified into species","Plankton diversity increases with pollution"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'co-evolution'?","answer":"Two or more species evolving in response to each other over time","choices":["Two species merging into one","Two or more species evolving in response to each other over time","Related species evolving differently","Parallel evolution in isolated habitats"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'adaptive radiation'?","answer":"Rapid diversification of one ancestral species into many species filling different niches","choices":["An animal adapting to radiation exposure","Rapid diversification of one ancestral species into many species filling different niches","A species colonizing a new continent","Evolution in response to climate change"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'niche construction'?","answer":"When an organism modifies its environment, altering selection pressures on itself and others","choices":["Building nests and burrows","When an organism modifies its environment, altering selection pressures on itself and others","Choosing the best habitat available","A species creating new ecological niches"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'phenotypic plasticity'?","answer":"The ability of an organism to change its characteristics in response to the environment","choices":["Random mutation producing new features","The ability of an organism to change its characteristics in response to the environment","A genetic trait that varies between individuals","Physical traits inherited from parents"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'ectothermy'?","answer":"Regulation of body temperature using external heat sources","choices":["Producing body heat internally","Regulation of body temperature using external heat sources","Having no temperature regulation","Using behavior to keep warm only in emergencies"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'endothermy'?","answer":"Generating and maintaining body heat internally through metabolism","choices":["Absorbing heat from the environment","Generating and maintaining body heat internally through metabolism","Lowering temperature during rest","Storing heat in thick fat layers"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'crypsis'?","answer":"The ability of an organism to avoid observation or detection by other organisms","choices":["Playing dead as a defense","The ability of an organism to avoid observation or detection by other organisms","Moving silently","Releasing a chemical deterrent"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'allelic frequency' in a population?","answer":"The proportion of each allele at a given locus in a population's gene pool","choices":["The number of genes an individual carries","The proportion of each allele at a given locus in a population's gene pool","The number of mutations per generation","How often each gene is expressed"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'ecological release'?","answer":"When an invasive or introduced species expands its niche in the absence of usual predators or competitors","choices":["When a population rebounds after hunting bans","When an invasive or introduced species expands its niche in the absence of usual predators or competitors","When a keystone species is reintroduced","Animals thriving after habitat restoration"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'kin recognition' in animals?","answer":"The ability to identify and behave differently toward relatives compared to non-relatives","choices":["Animals recognizing members of their own species","The ability to identify and behave differently toward relatives compared to non-relatives","Imprinting on the parent at birth","Identifying group members by smell"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'polyandry' in animal mating systems?","answer":"One female mating with multiple males","choices":["One male mating with multiple females","One female mating with multiple males","All members of a group mating freely","Mating between closely related individuals"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'polygyny'?","answer":"One male mating with multiple females","choices":["One female mating with multiple males","Multiple males and females all mating with each other","One male mating with multiple females","A group mating system with no clear roles"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'regressive evolution'?","answer":"The loss of complex structures that are no longer useful in an organism's environment","choices":["Evolving backwards toward earlier forms","The loss of complex structures that are no longer useful in an organism's environment","A mutation that reduces fitness","Random deterioration of genes"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'mass extinction' that killed the non-avian dinosaurs called?","answer":"The Cretaceous-Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event","choices":["The Permian extinction","The Triassic extinction","The Cretaceous-Paleogene (K-Pg) extinction event","The Devonian extinction"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'evolutionarily stable strategy' (ESS)?","answer":"A behavioral strategy that, when adopted by most of the population, cannot be displaced by any other strategy","choices":["The most common behavior in a population","A behavioral strategy that, when adopted by most of the population, cannot be displaced by any other strategy","A cooperation strategy that benefits all members","The strategy used by the dominant individual"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'biogeography'?","answer":"The study of the geographic distribution of species and ecosystems","choices":["The study of animal migration routes","The study of the geographic distribution of species and ecosystems","The distribution of marine habitats","Mapping the locations of endangered species"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'Cambrian explosion'?","answer":"A rapid appearance of most major animal body plans in the fossil record ~540 million years ago","choices":["A volcanic event that triggered rapid evolution","A rapid appearance of most major animal body plans in the fossil record ~540 million years ago","The mass extinction that cleared the way for vertebrates","The rapid spread of life to land from the sea"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'epibenthic' versus 'endobenthic' in marine biology?","answer":"Epibenthic lives on the seafloor surface; endobenthic lives within the substrate","choices":["Epibenthic is open water; endobenthic is near-shore","Epibenthic lives on the seafloor surface; endobenthic lives within the substrate","Epibenthic is carnivorous; endobenthic is filter-feeding","Epibenthic uses camouflage; endobenthic burrows to hide"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'chemical ecology'?","answer":"The study of chemical signals and substances that mediate interactions between organisms","choices":["Using chemistry to identify animal species","The study of chemical signals and substances that mediate interactions between organisms","Studying pollution effects on animals","The chemistry of animal digestion"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'metapopulation'?","answer":"A group of separated populations of the same species that interact through migration","choices":["A population spread across a very large area","A group of separated populations of the same species that interact through migration","Multiple species living in the same habitat","The combined population of two merged species"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'theropod' in paleontology?","answer":"A bipedal dinosaur group that includes the ancestors of birds","choices":["Any plant-eating dinosaur","A bipedal dinosaur group that includes the ancestors of birds","A marine reptile of the Mesozoic","An armor-plated dinosaur"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'cryptic species'?","answer":"Species that look nearly identical but are genetically distinct and reproductively isolated","choices":["Endangered species hiding in remote areas","Species that look nearly identical but are genetically distinct and reproductively isolated","Animals that change appearance seasonally","Species discovered through fossil records only"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'neoteny'?","answer":"Retaining juvenile features into adulthood due to delayed development","choices":["Aging faster in captivity","Retaining juvenile features into adulthood due to delayed development","Growing larger than the normal adult size","Reproducing before fully grown"]},
