{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'aposematic coloration' most effective against?","answer":"Visually hunting predators that can learn to associate color with bad experiences","choices":["Nocturnal predators","Visually hunting predators that can learn to associate color with bad experiences","All predators equally","Predators that use smell to hunt"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'dietary generalism' versus 'dietary specialism'?","answer":"Generalists eat many food types; specialists rely on a narrow range","choices":["Generalists survive better always","Generalists eat many food types; specialists rely on a narrow range","Specialists are always larger animals","Generalists eat more calories per day"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'biotelemetry'?","answer":"Using electronic tags to track the movements and physiology of wild animals","choices":["Measuring animal brainwaves in labs","Using electronic tags to track the movements and physiology of wild animals","Analyzing the sounds animals make","Remote sensing of habitat changes"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'intrasexual selection'?","answer":"Competition between members of the same sex for mating opportunities","choices":["Females choosing the best males","Competition between members of the same sex for mating opportunities","Both sexes displaying for each other","Mate guarding after pairing"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'intersexual selection'?","answer":"One sex choosing mates based on the traits of the other sex","choices":["Males and females competing with each other","One sex choosing mates based on the traits of the other sex","Physical combat between rivals","Seasonal mate changes"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'supernormal stimulus'?","answer":"An exaggerated imitation of a natural stimulus that produces a stronger response than the real thing","choices":["A predator too large for prey to respond to","An exaggerated imitation of a natural stimulus that produces a stronger response than the real thing","A stimulus from an entirely new environment","A sound too high-pitched for animals to hear"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'population viability analysis' (PVA)?","answer":"A method used to estimate the likelihood of a population's survival over time","choices":["Counting how many animals live in an area","A method used to estimate the likelihood of a population's survival over time","Tracking invasive species populations","Analyzing the genetic health of a population"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'endoparasitism'?","answer":"Parasitism occurring inside the host's body","choices":["Parasitism on the host's skin surface","Parasitism occurring inside the host's body","Parasites that sterilize their host","Parasites that kill their host quickly"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'ectoparasitism'?","answer":"Parasitism occurring on the outside of the host's body","choices":["Parasitism occurring on the outside of the host's body","Parasitism occurring inside the host's body","Parasites that live near but not on their host","Social parasites that infiltrate colonies"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'age structure' in a population?","answer":"The distribution of individuals among different age groups","choices":["The average age of animals in a habitat","The distribution of individuals among different age groups","The lifespan of each age cohort","Growth rate relative to age"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'environmental stochasticity'?","answer":"Random variation in environmental conditions that affects population survival","choices":["Predictable climate cycles affecting populations","Random variation in environmental conditions that affects population survival","Human disturbances to ecosystems","Long-term evolutionary pressures"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the function of 'countershading' in marine animals?","answer":"Dark on top and light on bottom disrupts the depth cue caused by sunlight from above","choices":["Reflecting sunlight to stay cool","Dark on top and light on bottom disrupts the depth cue caused by sunlight from above","Attracting mates in clear water","Absorbing heat in cold oceans"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'automimicry'?","answer":"When a non-toxic part of an animal resembles a toxic or warning-colored part","choices":["Mimicking a different species","When a non-toxic part of an animal resembles a toxic or warning-colored part","Changing color to match background automatically","Copying the display of a rival"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'iteroparity'?","answer":"Reproducing multiple times over the course of a lifetime","choices":["Reproducing once per year","Reproducing multiple times over the course of a lifetime","Reproducing in multiple locations","Reproducing with multiple partners"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'heterochrony' in evolution?","answer":"Changes in the timing or rate of developmental events between ancestor and descendant","choices":["Two species evolving at different speeds","Changes in the timing or rate of developmental events between ancestor and descendant","Adaptations that occur during a single lifetime","Different species sharing the same growth patterns"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What are 'extremophiles'?","answer":"Organisms that thrive in extreme environmental conditions such as heat, cold, or high acidity","choices":["Animals with extreme defensive adaptations","Organisms that thrive in extreme environmental conditions such as heat, cold, or high acidity","Species living at the limits of their range","Animals that seek out the most challenging habitats"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'ecological resilience'?","answer":"The ability of an ecosystem to absorb disturbance and reorganize to retain similar function","choices":["How quickly animals return after a disaster","The ability of an ecosystem to absorb disturbance and reorganize to retain similar function","The resistance of a species to disease","The size of a habitat needed to sustain a population"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'polygynandry'?","answer":"A mating system where multiple males and multiple females all mate with each other","choices":["One male with multiple females","One female with multiple males","A mating system where multiple males and multiple females all mate with each other","Mating for life in large groups"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is 'character convergence' in evolution?","answer":"When two species living in the same area become more similar over time due to shared selection pressures","choices":["Two separate species merging through interbreeding","When two species living in the same area become more similar over time due to shared selection pressures","Two unrelated species developing identical traits","Species losing distinctive features over time"]},
{"tier":4,"question":"What is the 'dear enemy effect'?","answer":"Animals respond less aggressively to familiar neighbors than to strangers","choices":["Animals that live near humans become tame","Animals respond less aggressively to familiar neighbors than to strangers","Predators avoid prey they see regularly","Animals warn neighbors of approaching predators"]},
# tier 5 (need ~85 more)
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'genomic imprinting'?","answer":"Gene expression differs depending on whether the gene was inherited from the mother or father","choices":["The genome reflects the environment","Gene expression differs depending on whether the gene was inherited from the mother or father","Genes imprint behaviors on the brain","Identical twins share perfectly imprinted genes"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is the 'Baldwin effect'?","answer":"Learned behaviors can guide natural selection if they repeatedly lead to advantageous conditions","choices":["Animals learn to change their genes","Learned behaviors can guide natural selection if they repeatedly lead to advantageous conditions","Cultural transmission replaces genetic evolution","Behavior is always more plastic than morphology"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'epigenetics' in the context of animal biology?","answer":"Changes in gene expression not involving changes to DNA sequence, often environmentally influenced","choices":["Evolution faster than Darwinian rates","Changes in gene expression not involving changes to DNA sequence, often environmentally influenced","The study of animal behavior across generations","Genetic mutations passed only through the mother"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'pleiotropy'?","answer":"One gene affecting multiple traits simultaneously","choices":["Multiple genes controlling one trait","One gene affecting multiple traits simultaneously","Genes carried on multiple chromosomes","Genes affecting only one sex"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'frequency-dependent selection'?","answer":"The fitness of a phenotype depends on how common or rare it is in the population","choices":["Selection pressure that increases with population density","The fitness of a phenotype depends on how common or rare it is in the population","Rare traits are always selected against","Selection favoring the most common traits"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'molecular clock' hypothesis?","answer":"DNA accumulates mutations at a roughly constant rate, allowing dating of divergence events","choices":["Cells contain timing mechanisms for reproduction","DNA accumulates mutations at a roughly constant rate, allowing dating of divergence events","Species evolve faster in warm climates","Mitochondrial genes change faster than nuclear genes"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'synteny' in genomics?","answer":"The conservation of gene order on chromosomes across different species","choices":["Genes with identical functions in different species","The conservation of gene order on chromosomes across different species","Shared regulatory sequences between species","Genes inherited without recombination"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'bet-hedging' as a life history strategy?","answer":"Reducing variance in fitness across variable environments at the cost of average fitness","choices":["Diversifying breeding sites to reduce predation","Reducing variance in fitness across variable environments at the cost of average fitness","Producing multiple litters per season","Delaying reproduction until conditions are ideal"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'phenotypic integration'?","answer":"The degree to which multiple traits are correlated and evolve together","choices":["The total phenotype of an organism","The degree to which multiple traits are correlated and evolve together","The integration of genotype and phenotype","How individual traits change over a lifetime"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'phylogeography'?","answer":"The study of the geographic distribution of genetic lineages within and among species","choices":["Mapping the migration routes of ancient species","The study of the geographic distribution of genetic lineages within and among species","Reconstructing the habitats of extinct species","Genetic differences between island and mainland populations"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is the 'neutral theory of molecular evolution'?","answer":"Most molecular changes are neutral (not selected for or against) and spread by genetic drift","choices":["Evolution is driven by environment, not competition","Most molecular changes are neutral (not selected for or against) and spread by genetic drift","Only beneficial mutations accumulate over time","Evolution at the molecular level is faster than at morphological level"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'prezygotic isolation'?","answer":"Barriers to reproduction that prevent the formation of a zygote","choices":["Barriers that prevent embryo development","Barriers to reproduction that prevent the formation of a zygote","Competition between sperm from different males","The inability of hybrids to survive"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'postzygotic isolation'?","answer":"Barriers to reproduction after fertilization, such as hybrid sterility or inviability","choices":["Barriers that prevent fertilization","Barriers to reproduction after fertilization, such as hybrid sterility or inviability","One species out-competing another after mating","Behavioral differences preventing mating"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'sensory drive' in the evolution of communication signals?","answer":"Signals evolve to match the sensory environment and the receiver's perceptual system","choices":["Animals evolve stronger senses over time","Signals evolve to match the sensory environment and the receiver's perceptual system","Predators evolve to jam prey communication","Sensory overload triggers fight-or-flight"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'conflict of interest between the sexes' in evolutionary biology?","answer":"Males and females have different optimal reproductive strategies, causing evolutionary conflicts","choices":["Males and females compete for the same food","Males and females have different optimal reproductive strategies, causing evolutionary conflicts","Only one sex controls mating in each species","Males and females have different lifespans"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'honest advertisement' in animal signaling?","answer":"Costly signals that reliably convey the signaler's condition because only high-quality individuals can produce them","choices":["Animals always signal truthfully","Costly signals that reliably convey the signaler's condition because only high-quality individuals can produce them","Warning signals that indicate real danger","Color patterns that match actual toxicity"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'cultural transmission' in animal behavior?","answer":"The spread of behaviors within a population through social learning rather than genetics","choices":["Teaching offspring to hunt","The spread of behaviors within a population through social learning rather than genetics","Animals adopting human behaviors","Behaviors that replace genetic instincts"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'clade' in phylogenetics?","answer":"A group consisting of an ancestor and all of its descendants","choices":["A cluster of related species","A group consisting of an ancestor and all of its descendants","A grade of similarly complex organisms","Species sharing a common habitat"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'synapomorphy'?","answer":"A shared derived character state inherited from a common ancestor","choices":["A trait shared by all animals","A shared derived character state inherited from a common ancestor","A trait common to an entire order","Convergent features in unrelated taxa"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'evolutionary constraint'?","answer":"A limitation on the range of phenotypes that natural selection can produce in a lineage","choices":["Competition preventing rapid evolution","A limitation on the range of phenotypes that natural selection can produce in a lineage","An adaptation that cannot be lost once evolved","A developmental stage that prevents change"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'reaction norm'?","answer":"The pattern of phenotypes produced by a single genotype across a range of environments","choices":["The range of environments a species can survive in","The pattern of phenotypes produced by a single genotype across a range of environments","The limits of behavioral flexibility","How rapidly an organism adapts to change"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ecological speciation'?","answer":"Speciation driven by divergent natural selection from contrasting environments","choices":["Speciation caused by habitat destruction","Speciation driven by divergent natural selection from contrasting environments","Speciation triggered by genetic mutation only","Speciation caused by geographic barriers"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'evo-devo'?","answer":"Evolutionary developmental biology — how changes in developmental genes produce new morphologies","choices":["The study of ancient animal development","Evolutionary developmental biology — how changes in developmental genes produce new morphologies","Evolution of behavior in developing animals","Development of evolutionary theory over time"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'genome size paradox' (C-value enigma)?","answer":"Some simple organisms have larger genomes than complex ones, suggesting genome size is not proportional to complexity","choices":["Complex animals have more genes than simple ones","Some simple organisms have larger genomes than complex ones, suggesting genome size is not proportional to complexity","Larger animals always have larger genomes","Mammals have the largest genomes"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'gene flow'?","answer":"The transfer of genetic variation from one population to another through migration and interbreeding","choices":["Genetic drift in small populations","The transfer of genetic variation from one population to another through migration and interbreeding","The expression of genes in different environments","Random mutations spreading through a population"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'balancing selection'?","answer":"Natural selection that maintains multiple alleles in a population (e.g., heterozygote advantage)","choices":["Selection that produces no net change","Natural selection that maintains multiple alleles in a population (e.g., heterozygote advantage)","Selection that favors the average phenotype","Equal survival rates across all phenotypes"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'transgenerational epigenetic inheritance'?","answer":"Epigenetic changes acquired in one generation are passed to offspring","choices":["Traits learned by parents are always passed on","Epigenetic changes acquired in one generation are passed to offspring","All genetic mutations affect the next generation","Cultural behaviors transmitted through DNA"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'population genetics'?","answer":"The study of genetic variation and its change within and between populations","choices":["The genetics of population-level diseases","The study of genetic variation and its change within and between populations","Measuring the size and density of populations","Genetics of breeding programs in zoos"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'dispersal limitation'?","answer":"The failure of a species to reach a suitable habitat due to barriers to movement","choices":["Animals unable to move due to injury","The failure of a species to reach a suitable habitat due to barriers to movement","Slow reproduction limiting population spread","Territorial behavior limiting range expansion"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'sexual conflict'?","answer":"Opposing selection pressures on males and females that can lead to evolutionary arms races","choices":["Males and females competing for the same food","Opposing selection pressures on males and females that can lead to evolutionary arms races","Male competition for access to females","Female choice reducing male diversity"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'life history theory'?","answer":"The study of how natural selection shapes the timing and pattern of growth, reproduction, and death","choices":["The study of animal biographies","The study of how natural selection shapes the timing and pattern of growth, reproduction, and death","How animals learn survival skills","The stages of a species' evolutionary history"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ring species'?","answer":"A series of adjacent populations where neighboring populations can interbreed but the two end populations cannot","choices":["A circular migration route","A series of adjacent populations where neighboring populations can interbreed but the two end populations cannot","Species that evolved on circular islands","Populations connected by a ring of habitat"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'parasitoid'?","answer":"An organism that lays eggs in a host; larvae develop inside and kill the host","choices":["A parasite that slowly weakens its host","An organism that lays eggs in a host; larvae develop inside and kill the host","A parasite that lives entirely on the host's skin","A large predator that also feeds on smaller parasites"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'exaptation'?","answer":"A trait that evolved for one function is co-opted for a new function","choices":["A trait that is no longer useful","A trait that evolved for one function is co-opted for a new function","Rapid evolution of multiple traits at once","Evolution producing the same trait twice"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'arms race' in predator-prey evolution?","answer":"Reciprocal adaptations where each party evolves counter-responses to the other's evolution","choices":["Predators always winning evolution over time","Reciprocal adaptations where each party evolves counter-responses to the other's evolution","Prey evolving speed while predators evolve camouflage","Only predators driving evolutionary change"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'mate-choice copying'?","answer":"Individuals choosing mates based on observed mating decisions by others","choices":["Choosing a mate based on parent preferences","Individuals choosing mates based on observed mating decisions by others","Females copying male display behaviors","Males competing by imitating rivals"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'character release' in an island population?","answer":"In the absence of competitors, a species may expand its niche and show greater individual variation","choices":["A species becoming tamer after isolation","In the absence of competitors, a species may expand its niche and show greater individual variation","Traits becoming fixed without pressure","Rapid evolution toward a mainland ancestor"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'niche conservatism'?","answer":"The tendency for species to retain ancestral ecological traits rather than evolving new niches","choices":["Conserving habitat for endangered niches","The tendency for species to retain ancestral ecological traits rather than evolving new niches","Maintaining behavior patterns learned in youth","Avoiding niche overlap with competitors"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'spandrel' in evolutionary biology (Gould and Lewontin)?","answer":"A byproduct of an adaptation that has no direct selective value itself but may acquire functions later","choices":["A structural trait with no known function","A byproduct of an adaptation that has no direct selective value itself but may acquire functions later","A vestigial organ","A trait shared by all members of a clade"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'macroevolution'?","answer":"Evolutionary change at or above the species level, producing new taxa","choices":["Very rapid evolution","Evolutionary change at or above the species level, producing new taxa","Changes in gene frequency within a population","Evolution of large body size"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'unit of selection' debate in evolutionary biology?","answer":"Whether selection primarily acts on genes, individuals, or groups","choices":["How to measure the strength of selection","Whether selection primarily acts on genes, individuals, or groups","Which traits are most commonly selected","Which environments produce the most evolution"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'condition-dependent handicap'?","answer":"A signal whose cost is proportional to the signaler's condition, so only fit individuals can afford it","choices":["A disability that helps find better mates","A signal whose cost is proportional to the signaler's condition, so only fit individuals can afford it","A trait that is costly to all individuals equally","A physical feature that impairs survival but attracts mates"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ecological trap'?","answer":"When organisms are attracted to a habitat of low quality, lowering their fitness","choices":["A habitat too small to support a population","When organisms are attracted to a habitat of low quality, lowering their fitness","A habitat surrounded by barriers","A specialist species unable to adapt to a new environment"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'trophic level'?","answer":"The position an organism occupies in a food chain based on its feeding role","choices":["The depth at which marine organisms feed","The position an organism occupies in a food chain based on its feeding role","The number of prey items an organism eats","The energy content of food at each stage"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'phylogenetic signal'?","answer":"The tendency for closely related species to resemble each other more than expected by chance","choices":["A DNA sequence shared by a whole phylum","The tendency for closely related species to resemble each other more than expected by chance","A marker used to trace evolution","The genetic signal used to reconstruct family trees"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'Cope's rule'?","answer":"The tendency for body size to increase over evolutionary time within a lineage","choices":["Predators are always larger than their prey","The tendency for body size to increase over evolutionary time within a lineage","Complex organisms evolve faster than simple ones","Island species tend to shrink over time"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'olfactory communication' in mammals?","answer":"Using chemical scent signals (pheromones, gland secretions) to convey information to other individuals","choices":["Communicating through high-frequency sounds","Using chemical scent signals (pheromones, gland secretions) to convey information to other individuals","Visual displays that indicate dominance","Tactile signals used during grooming"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'parental investment theory' (Trivers)?","answer":"The sex that invests more in offspring is the choosier sex; the less-investing sex competes more for mates","choices":["Parents always invest equally in offspring","The sex that invests more in offspring is the choosier sex; the less-investing sex competes more for mates","Larger species invest more than smaller ones","Females always choose mates; males always compete"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ecophysiology'?","answer":"The study of how environmental factors influence an organism's physiological processes","choices":["The ecology of plant physiology","The study of how environmental factors influence an organism's physiological processes","How ecosystems regulate global physiology","The energy budget of a whole ecosystem"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'carry capacity' (K) in population ecology?","answer":"The maximum population size an environment can sustain indefinitely","choices":["The weight an animal can carry","The maximum population size an environment can sustain indefinitely","The population density at which reproduction peaks","The growth rate of a population at low density"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'source-sink dynamics'?","answer":"Productive (source) habitats supply dispersing individuals that sustain populations in poor (sink) habitats","choices":["Drainage patterns determining animal movement","Productive (source) habitats supply dispersing individuals that sustain populations in poor (sink) habitats","Animals moving between water and land","Seasonal flooding determining habitat quality"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'character state' in cladistics?","answer":"A specific condition of a morphological or molecular attribute used to classify organisms","choices":["The dominant trait in a population","A specific condition of a morphological or molecular attribute used to classify organisms","The genetic blueprint of a species","The set of behaviors defining a clade"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ecological stoichiometry'?","answer":"The study of the balance of chemical elements in ecological interactions","choices":["The chemical analysis of soil","The study of the balance of chemical elements in ecological interactions","Measuring toxins in the food chain","How chemical defenses evolve in plants and animals"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'neuroethology'?","answer":"The study of the neural mechanisms underlying natural animal behavior","choices":["Animal behavior under stress","The study of the neural mechanisms underlying natural animal behavior","How nervous system size relates to intelligence","The evolution of the vertebrate brain"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'predator-prey cycle' (Lotka-Volterra)?","answer":"Predator and prey populations oscillate, with prey peaks followed by predator peaks then crashes","choices":["Predators always control prey numbers","Predator and prey populations oscillate, with prey peaks followed by predator peaks then crashes","Prey evolve faster than predators","Predators always go extinct if prey become scarce"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'sexual arms race'?","answer":"Escalating co-evolutionary conflict between male and female reproductive strategies","choices":["Males fighting until only one survives","Escalating co-evolutionary conflict between male and female reproductive strategies","Both sexes evolving more elaborate displays","Selection for larger body size in both sexes"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'cryptic female choice'?","answer":"After mating, females use physiological mechanisms to select among sperm from different males","choices":["Females choosing mates without being observed","After mating, females use physiological mechanisms to select among sperm from different males","Females hiding offspring from males","Silent courtship behaviors females use to accept mates"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'ecological fitting'?","answer":"Organisms use pre-existing traits to interact with novel environments or hosts without evolving new traits","choices":["Rapid adaptation to a new habitat","Organisms use pre-existing traits to interact with novel environments or hosts without evolving new traits","Animals fitting perfectly into their niche","Specialization producing perfect ecological roles"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'signal evolution' in the context of receiver psychology?","answer":"Signals evolve to exploit pre-existing sensory biases in receivers rather than being entirely arbitrary","choices":["Signals become louder over evolutionary time","Signals evolve to exploit pre-existing sensory biases in receivers rather than being entirely arbitrary","Both sender and receiver evolve at the same rate","Signal complexity tracks predation pressure"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'genomic conflict'?","answer":"Genetic elements within the same organism competing to increase their own transmission at cost to others","choices":["Competition between organisms for reproductive access","Genetic elements within the same organism competing to increase their own transmission at cost to others","Conflict between a parasite's genes and the host's","Different genes controlling opposite traits"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'landscape genetics'?","answer":"How landscape features influence gene flow and genetic variation across space","choices":["How climate shapes animal distributions","How landscape features influence gene flow and genetic variation across space","Studying genetics at the continental scale","How habitats are classified by dominant species"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'functional morphology'?","answer":"The study of how the structure and form of organisms relate to their function","choices":["The study of how muscles work","The study of how the structure and form of organisms relate to their function","Classifying species by body shape","How size affects behavior"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'bet-hedging via variable offspring quality'?","answer":"Producing offspring with varied phenotypes to ensure some survive unpredictable conditions","choices":["Having more offspring than strictly necessary","Producing offspring with varied phenotypes to ensure some survive unpredictable conditions","Raising some offspring with extra care","Delaying all reproduction until conditions stabilize"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'trophic mismatch'?","answer":"Misalignment between peak food availability and the timing of reproduction, often linked to climate change","choices":["A predator in the wrong habitat","Misalignment between peak food availability and the timing of reproduction, often linked to climate change","Animals competing for food outside their trophic level","A species eating from too many trophic levels"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'obligate mutualism'?","answer":"A mutualistic relationship where both species depend on the interaction for survival","choices":["Cooperation that occurs only in certain conditions","A mutualistic relationship where both species depend on the interaction for survival","A temporary alliance between predator species","Two species that evolved simultaneously in isolation"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'local adaptation'?","answer":"Populations evolving genotypes better suited to their own local environment than to other environments","choices":["Any adaptation occurring in a specific region","Populations evolving genotypes better suited to their own local environment than to other environments","Rapid adaptation in urban environments","A species restricted to a single location"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'diffuse co-evolution'?","answer":"Evolutionary responses to multiple species rather than one-to-one co-evolution","choices":["Co-evolution that happens slowly","Evolutionary responses to multiple species rather than one-to-one co-evolution","Co-evolution driven by climate","Unrelated species affecting each other indirectly"]},
{"tier":5,"question":"What is 'phylogenetic comparative method'?","answer":"Using evolutionary trees to account for shared ancestry when comparing trait variation across species","choices":["Comparing ancient and modern species","Using evolutionary trees to account for shared ancestry when comparing trait variation across species","A method for dating fossils","Building species trees from behavioral data"]},
